// NCE — Part 3 (Q121-210)
var _qs = window.QUESTIONS_DATA["nce"] || (window.QUESTIONS_DATA["nce"] = []);

_qs.push(
{id:"nce-121",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'positive psychology' (Seligman)?",options:["Optimism only","The scientific study of well-being, strengths, and flourishing; building on what's right rather than fixing what's wrong","A medical model","A type of CBT"],answer:1,explanation:"Positive psychology (Seligman) studies well-being, strengths, meaning, and flourishing. PERMA model: Positive emotions, Engagement, Relationships, Meaning, Accomplishment. Character strengths (24 VIA strengths). Not naive optimism — complements traditional psychology with what's right, not just what's wrong."},
{id:"nce-122",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'PERMA' model of well-being (Seligman)?",options:["A medical model","Positive emotions, Engagement, Relationships, Meaning, Accomplishment — five elements of well-being","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"PERMA (Seligman): Positive emotions (life satisfaction), Engagement (flow, using strengths), Relationships (social connection), Meaning (purpose, belonging to something bigger), Accomplishment (achievement, mastery). A model for flourishing, used in positive psychology and coaching interventions."},
{id:"nce-123",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'flow' (Csikszentmihalyi)?",options:["Boredom","A state of deep, effortless engagement in an activity (challenges match skills); a key to engagement and well-being","A medical symptom","A type of meditation"],answer:1,explanation:"Flow (Csikszentmihalyi): deep, effortless engagement. Conditions: high challenge + high skill (matched), clear goals, immediate feedback, deep concentration, loss of self-consciousness, sense of control, time distortion. Also called being 'in the zone.' Supports engagement and well-being."},
{id:"nce-124",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'VIA Character Strengths' (Peterson, Seligman)?",options:["A diagnosis","24 character strengths (e.g., curiosity, bravery, kindness) measured by the VIA Inventory; used to identify personal strengths","A medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"VIA Character Strengths (Peterson & Seligman): 24 strengths organized under 6 virtues (wisdom, courage, humanity, justice, temperance, transcendence). Examples: curiosity, creativity, bravery, perseverance, honesty, kindness, love, teamwork, fairness, leadership, forgiveness, humility, prudence, self-regulation, appreciation of beauty, gratitude, hope, humor, spirituality. Free survey at viacharacter.org."},
{id:"nce-125",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'growth mindset' (Dweck)?",options:["A fixed view","The belief that abilities and intelligence can be developed through effort, learning, and persistence","A medical condition","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Growth mindset (Dweck): abilities and intelligence are developable. Effort, learning, and persistence lead to growth. Compare to fixed mindset: abilities are static. The mindset affects resilience, motivation, and response to failure. Praised for process (not just outcomes) helps develop growth mindset."},
{id:"nce-126",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'resilience'?",options:["Not feeling stress","The process of adapting well in the face of adversity, trauma, tragedy, threats, or significant stress","A personality trait","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Resilience: the process of adapting well in adversity, trauma, tragedy, threats, or significant stress. Not a fixed trait but a process. Factors: positive relationships, problem-solving, self-efficacy, hope, emotional regulation, social support, meaning-making. Protective factors can be built and strengthened."},
{id:"nce-127",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'post-traumatic growth' (Tedeschi & Calhoun)?",options:["Avoiding trauma","Positive psychological change experienced as a result of struggle with traumatic circumstances","A medical outcome","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Post-traumatic growth (Tedeschi & Calhoun): positive changes that may follow trauma. Five areas: greater appreciation of life, deeper relationships, increased personal strength, recognition of new possibilities, spiritual/religious growth. Distinct from resilience (adapting well) — it's about growth."},
{id:"nce-128",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'grief'?",options:["A mental illness","A normal, natural response to loss; usually time-limited; complex or prolonged grief may require intervention","A type of depression","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Grief: normal, natural response to loss (death, divorce, job, health, etc.). Manifests emotionally (sadness, anger, guilt), cognitively (denial, confusion, preoccupation), physically (sleep, appetite, fatigue), socially (withdrawal). The 'stages' (Kübler-Ross: denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance) is a model, not a linear process. Prolonged grief disorder is a diagnosis."},
{id:"nce-129",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'complicated grief' (prolonged grief disorder)?",options:["Normal grief","Intense, prolonged grief symptoms (yearning, preoccupation, identity disruption) lasting more than 12 months (adults) or longer (children) after loss, causing significant impairment","A depression","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Prolonged grief disorder (DSM-5-TR criteria): persistent and pervasive grief response characterized by yearning/longing for the deceased and intense emotional pain. Symptoms last more than 12 months in adults (6 months in children) and cause significant functional impairment. The condition is now formally recognized in DSM-5-TR."},
{id:"nce-130",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'dual process model' of bereavement (Stroebe & Schut)?",options:["A linear model","A model with two oscillating processes: loss-oriented (grief work) and restoration-oriented (adjusting to life changes)","A medical model","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Dual process model (Stroebe & Schut, 1999): bereavement involves oscillation between two processes — loss-oriented (grief, yearning, sadness) and restoration-oriented (mastering new tasks, attending to life changes). Grief is dynamic, not linear. Counselors help clients move between the two."},
{id:"nce-131",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'meaning-making' in grief counseling?",options:["Avoiding pain","Helping the client find meaning in the loss, integrate the experience, and continue living with purpose","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Meaning-making (Neimeyer, Rando): central in grief counseling. The client integrates the loss into their life story and identity. Includes: meaning of the loss, meaning of the deceased's life and influence, meaning of ongoing life, and meaning in suffering. Re-authoring the narrative. Logotherapy (Frankl) also applies."},
{id:"nce-132",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'continuing bonds' theory of grief (Klass, Silverman & Nickman)?",options:["Cut off from the deceased","The bereaved maintain a continuing inner relationship with the deceased (vs. detaching)","A type of pathology","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Continuing bonds (Klass et al.): the bereaved maintain an ongoing, evolving relationship with the deceased (through memories, objects, rituals, internalized values). Replaces the older 'letting go' view. Healthy grief involves ongoing connection, not detachment. The bonds change but persist."},
{id:"nce-133",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'crisis' in counseling?",options:["A chronic issue","A perceived or actual precipitating event that causes an imbalance in an individual's usual functioning and coping","A type of personality","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"A crisis (caplan, James & Gilliland): an acute disruption of the usual balance, where the person's usual coping mechanisms fail. Crisis types: developmental, situational, existential, environmental. May lead to growth or deterioration. Time-limited, intervention-focused. Goals: safety, stabilization, connection to resources, restoration."},
{id:"nce-134",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Roberts' 7-stage crisis intervention model'?",options:["A psychoanalytic model","Define the problem, ensure client safety, provide support, examine alternatives, make plans, obtain commitment, follow up","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Roberts' 7-stage crisis model: (1) define the problem, (2) ensure client safety, (3) provide support, (4) examine alternatives, (5) make plans, (6) obtain commitment, (7) follow up with appropriate referrals. Time-limited and pragmatic. May be combined with safety planning for suicidality."},
{id:"nce-135",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'James & Gilliland' crisis intervention approach?",options:["A long-term therapy","A stepped, ABC model: A (attitudinal), B (behavioral), C (cognitive), with focus on safety, support, and skills","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"James & Gilliland: crisis intervention framework. Three sets of skills: A (attitudinal — hope, neutrality), B (behavioral — safety, environmental control, action), C (cognitive — insight, challenge, alternatives). Also: safe, support, self-awareness, self-care, self-determination. Stepped approach based on crisis type."},
{id:"nce-136",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'suicide risk assessment'?",options:["A diagnosis","A structured evaluation of risk factors, warning signs, protective factors, plan, means, intent, and history","A test","A legal document"],answer:1,explanation:"Suicide risk assessment: structured (C-SSRS, SAFE-T, PHQ-9 item 9). Evaluate: ideation (passive vs. active), plan (specificity, lethality, means access), intent, prior attempts, history, risk factors, protective factors, warning signs. Document. Always err on side of safety. Hospitalize if imminent risk."},
{id:"nce-137",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'means restriction' as a suicide prevention strategy?",options:["A diagnosis","Limiting access to lethal means (firearms, medications, etc.) to prevent suicide attempts","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Means restriction: reducing access to lethal means. Strong evidence base (Mann et al., 2005). Counseling clients (and families) on safe storage of firearms, medications, etc. Reduces suicide rates. Most effective when combined with other strategies. Part of safety planning and the SPI."},
{id:"nce-138",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Stanley-Brown Safety Planning Intervention' (SPI)?",options:["A medication","A written, collaborative safety plan with warning signs, coping strategies, support contacts, and emergency numbers","A test","A legal document"],answer:1,explanation:"SPI (Stanley & Brown): a written, collaborative safety plan created with the client. Includes: warning signs, internal coping strategies, social contacts/distractions, professional contacts, lethal means restriction, reasons for living. Replaces no-suicide contracts. Evidence-based. Distribute and review."},
{id:"nce-139",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'postvention' after a suicide?",options:["Aftercare only","Activities and interventions to support survivors of suicide (family, friends, community) and reduce the risk of suicide contagion","A type of therapy","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Postvention: support after a suicide. Goal: help survivors grieve, reduce suicide contagion, support the bereaved, address guilt, provide community resources. Includes: outreach, support groups, memorialization, media guidelines. Important to avoid sensationalizing. Often coordinated by mental health professionals."},
{id:"nce-140",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'suicide contagion'?",options:["A virus","The spread of suicidal behavior from one person to another (e.g., media exposure, peer influence) — a real phenomenon, especially among youth","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Suicide contagion: the spread of suicidal behavior through exposure. Can be: direct (peers, family) or mediated (media, social media). Especially impactful in youth. Prevention: responsible media reporting, school-based postvention, support for bereaved. CDC and media guidelines address this."},
{id:"nce-141",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'harm reduction' (substance use)?",options:["Abstinence only","A pragmatic approach that meets clients where they are, reduces negative consequences of use without requiring abstinence as a precondition","A moral stance","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Harm reduction: pragmatic, compassionate approach. Goal: reduce the negative consequences of substance use (e.g., disease, death, harm to others). Examples: needle exchange, naloxone distribution, supervised consumption, safe drinking guidelines, fentanyl test strips. Doesn't require abstinence as precondition. Coexists with abstinence-based and MI approaches."},
{id:"nce-142",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'transtheoretical model' (Stages of Change)?",options:["A medical model","PC, C, P, A, M (and sometimes Relapse) — a model of intentional change with matching interventions","A type of medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"TTM (Prochaska & DiClemente): PC, C, P, A, M, and sometimes Relapse. Used in MI matching. Precontemplation (unaware), Contemplation (ambivalent), Preparation (planning), Action (active), Maintenance (sustaining). Interventions match the stage. Foundational to MI and many substance use treatments."},
{id:"nce-143",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'motivational interviewing' for substance use?",options:["Confrontation","A collaborative, client-centered approach that helps clients resolve ambivalence about change and elicit their own motivations","A diagnosis","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"MI (Miller & Rollnick): the gold standard for substance use treatment engagement. Evokes change talk, rolls with resistance, develops discrepancy, supports self-efficacy. Spirit: partnership, acceptance, compassion, evocation. Distinct from confrontational styles (which are less effective and risk dropout)."},
{id:"nce-144",q:"Which of the following BEST describes '12-step facilitation' (TSF)?",options:["A medical treatment","A structured approach that engages clients in 12-step programs like AA/NA as part of treatment","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"TSF (Nowinski, Baker, Carroll): a manual-guided approach to facilitate engagement in 12-step groups (AA, NA, etc.). Three key ideas: acceptance (powerlessness over addiction), surrender (to a higher power/self/group), and active involvement in meetings. Evidence-based for alcohol use disorder."},
{id:"nce-145",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'difference between substance use, abuse, and dependence'?",options:["Same thing","Use = any consumption; abuse (DSM-IV) = harmful use; dependence (addiction) = impaired control, tolerance, withdrawal, use despite harm","A medical issue","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"DSM-5 combines abuse and dependence into a single 'Substance Use Disorder' (mild, moderate, severe). DSM-IV-TR had separate abuse and dependence. Substance use = any consumption; harmful use = use causing problems; dependence = addiction (impaired control, tolerance, withdrawal). The NCE may use DSM-IV-TR or DSM-5 terminology."},
{id:"nce-146",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Substance Use Disorder' (SUD) criteria in DSM-5-TR?",options:["One symptom","11 criteria (use more than intended, unsuccessful efforts to cut down, withdrawal, tolerance, etc.); ≥2 symptoms in 12 months for diagnosis","A diagnosis","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"DSM-5-TR SUD: 11 criteria, grouped into 4 categories (impaired control, social impairment, risky use, pharmacological criteria). Severity: 2-3 = mild, 4-5 = moderate, ≥6 = severe. Includes alcohol, cannabis, opioid, stimulant, sedative, etc. Specifiers: in early remission, sustained remission, on agonist therapy, in a controlled environment."},
{id:"nce-147",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'tolerance' in SUD?",options:["Acceptance","A need for increased amounts of the substance to achieve the same effect, or diminished effect with continued same amount","A personality trait","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Tolerance: need for increased amounts to achieve the same effect, or diminished effect with continued use of the same amount. Pharmacological: metabolic (faster metabolism) or functional (decreased receptor response). Tachyphylaxis = rapid tolerance. Withdrawal symptoms appear when substance is reduced or stopped."},
{id:"nce-148",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'withdrawal' in SUD?",options:["A normal state","A set of physiological and cognitive symptoms that occur when blood/tissue levels of a substance decline after heavy prolonged use","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Withdrawal: physiological/cognitive symptoms after reduction or cessation of heavy, prolonged substance use. Causes significant distress/impairment. Examples: alcohol (tremors, seizures, DTs), opioids (N/V, muscle aches, lacrimation, diarrhea), benzodiazepines (anxiety, seizures, similar to alcohol), stimulants (fatigue, depression, increased appetite). Can be life-threatening."},
{id:"nce-149",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'medication-assisted treatment' (MAT) for opioid use disorder?",options:["Replacing one drug with another","The use of FDA-approved medications (methadone, buprenorphine, naltrexone) combined with counseling and behavioral therapies","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"MAT for OUD: medications (methadone, buprenorphine/Suboxone, naltrexone/Vivitrol) + counseling + behavioral therapy. Evidence-based; reduces mortality, cravings, withdrawal, illegal use. Stigma remains. 'Medication for Addiction Treatment' (MAT) is now often called 'Medications for Opioid Use Disorder' (MOUD) to reduce stigma."},
{id:"nce-150",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'naloxone' (Narcan)?",options:["A long-term treatment","An opioid antagonist that rapidly reverses opioid overdose by displacing opioids from receptors","A test","A maintenance medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Naloxone (Narcan, Evzio): an opioid antagonist. Reverses overdose within 1-2 minutes by displacing opioids from receptors. Short half-life (30-90 min), so multiple doses may be needed. Available as nasal spray (Narcan) and injectable. Public health initiative: distribute to people who use opioids, families, first responders."},
{id:"nce-151",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Alcohol Use Disorder' treatment?",options:["Medication only","Combination of medications (naltrexone, acamprosate, disulfiram), counseling (MI, CBT, TSF, behavioral couples therapy), peer support (AA, SMART Recovery), and continuing care","A diagnosis","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"AUD treatment: multimodal. Medications: naltrexone (reduces craving), acamprosate (maintenance), disulfiram (aversive). Psychosocial: MI, CBT, MET/CBT, TSF, behavioral couples therapy. Peer support: AA, SMART Recovery, LifeRing, secular options. Continuing care is critical — relapse is common."},
{id:"nce-152",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Codependency'?",options:["Mutual dependence","A pattern of behaviors where one's sense of self is enmeshed with another, often at the expense of one's own needs; enabling a person's harmful behavior","A healthy relationship","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Codependency: a set of maladaptive patterns where one's identity, worth, and behaviors are enmeshed with another (often an addict or dysfunctional person). Includes: enabling, low self-worth, control, denial, repression of emotions, dependence. Originated in chemical dependency treatment. Not in DSM, but useful concept."},
{id:"nce-153",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Al-Anon' and 'Nar-Anon'?",options:["Medical treatments","12-step mutual-help programs for family and friends of alcoholics/addicts, focused on detachment, acceptance, and self-care","A medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Al-Anon (alcohol), Nar-Anon (narcotics), Alateen (youth in alcoholic families): 12-step mutual-help groups for family and friends. Focus: detachment (with love), acceptance, self-care, working the steps. Separate from AA/NA. Evidence-based support. Many family members find this powerful."},
{id:"nce-154",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Anorexia Nervosa' (DSM-5-TR)?",options:["A normal diet","Restriction of energy intake, intense fear of gaining weight, and disturbance in body weight perception; significantly low body weight","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Anorexia: restriction of energy intake leading to significantly low body weight; intense fear of gaining weight; disturbance in self-perceived shape/weight. Subtypes: restricting type and binge-eating/purging type. Medical complications: bradycardia, hypotension, amenorrhea, osteoporosis, electrolyte abnormalities. Highest mortality of any mental disorder."},
{id:"nce-155",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Bulimia Nervosa' (DSM-5-TR)?",options:["Restriction only","Recurrent episodes of binge eating followed by compensatory behaviors (vomiting, laxatives, exercise, fasting) at least weekly for 3 months","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Bulimia: recurrent binge eating + recurrent compensatory behaviors (vomiting, laxatives, diuretics, fasting, excessive exercise) at least weekly for 3 months. Self-evaluation unduly influenced by body shape/weight. Body weight usually normal or above normal. Medical complications: dental erosion, electrolyte imbalance, parotid enlargement, esophagitis."},
{id:"nce-156",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Binge Eating Disorder' (DSM-5-TR)?",options:["Bulimia with purging","Recurrent binge eating without compensatory behaviors; marked distress about bingeing","Anorexia","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"BED: recurrent episodes of binge eating without regular compensatory behaviors. Marked distress about the binges. Eating much more rapidly than normal, until uncomfortably full, eating large amounts when not hungry, eating alone due to embarrassment, feeling disgusted/depressed/guilty afterward. Associated with obesity and weight concerns."},
{id:"nce-157",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'family-based treatment' (FBT) for adolescent anorexia?",options:["A medical model","A treatment that empowers parents to take responsibility for restoring their child's weight and health, with phased weight restoration, then hand-back of control","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"FBT (Maude, Lock, Le Grange) — also called the Maudsley approach. Three phases: (1) weight restoration (parents in charge of meals), (2) returning control to the adolescent, (3) establishing healthy adolescent identity. The most evidence-based treatment for adolescent anorexia. Parents as a resource, not blamed."},
{id:"nce-158",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Enhanced CBT' (CBT-E) for eating disorders?",options:["Psychoanalytic","A transdiagnostic, individualized CBT for eating disorders that targets maintaining mechanisms across diagnoses","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"CBT-E (Fairburn, 2008): transdiagnostic, individualized CBT for eating disorders. Targets the maintaining mechanisms (overvaluation of shape/weight, dietary restraint, eating disorder behaviors) across AN, BN, BED, OSFED. Strong evidence base. Includes formulations, weekly weighing, regular eating, and addressing body image."},
{id:"nce-159",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Bipolar I Disorder' (DSM-5-TR)?",options:["Depression only","A manic episode (lasting at least 7 days or requiring hospitalization), often followed by depressive episodes; may have psychotic features","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Bipolar I: at least one manic episode (≥1 week or requiring hospitalization). Mania: elevated/irritable mood, increased activity/energy, plus symptoms (grandiosity, decreased need for sleep, more talkative, flight of ideas, distractibility, increased goal-directed activity, risky behavior). May have psychotic features. Often followed by MDEs."},
{id:"nce-160",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'manic episode'?",options:["A good mood","A distinct period of elevated, expansive, or irritable mood and increased activity/energy, lasting at least 1 week (or any duration if hospitalization is needed)","A personality trait","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Manic episode: distinct period of abnormally elevated, expansive, or irritable mood and increased goal-directed activity/energy, lasting ≥1 week (or any duration if hospitalization needed). 3+ symptoms (DIGFAST): Distractibility, Impulsivity/risky behavior, Grandiosity, Flight of ideas, Activity increased, Sleep decreased, Talkativeness. Marked impairment or hospitalization."},
{id:"nce-161",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Bipolar II Disorder'?",options:["Same as Bipolar I","Hypomanic episodes (at least 4 consecutive days) plus major depressive episodes; no full manic episodes","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Bipolar II: hypomanic episodes (≥4 consecutive days, less severe than mania) + MDEs. Hypomania is distinct from normal mood, observable by others, but doesn't cause marked impairment, hospitalization, or psychosis. The depressive episodes are often more impairing. Misdiagnosis as MDD is common."},
{id:"nce-162",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'hypomania'?",options:["Same as mania","A less severe form of mania lasting at least 4 consecutive days; distinct from usual mood, observable, but no marked impairment or psychosis","A type of depression","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Hypomania: distinct period of elevated/irritable mood and increased activity, lasting ≥4 consecutive days. Less severe than mania — no marked impairment, hospitalization, or psychosis. The person usually functions well (sometimes even better). Observable by others. Must include 3+ DIG FAST symptoms."},
{id:"nce-163",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'cyclothymic disorder'?",options:["Bipolar II","A chronic, fluctuating mood disturbance with numerous periods of hypomanic and depressive symptoms for at least 2 years (1 year for children/adolescents), not meeting full criteria for hypomanic or MDE episodes","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Cyclothymia: chronic, fluctuating mood with numerous periods of hypomanic and depressive symptoms for at least 2 years (1 year for youth). The symptoms don't meet criteria for full hypomanic or MDE episodes. Symptom-free periods last ≤2 months. Often seen as a 'mild' form of bipolar but can cause significant distress."},
{id:"nce-164",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Schizophrenia'?",options:["Multiple personality","A psychotic disorder with two or more of the following for at least 1 month: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech, grossly disorganized or catatonic behavior, negative symptoms","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Schizophrenia: 2+ of 5 symptoms (delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech, grossly disorganized/catatonic behavior, negative symptoms) for ≥1 month (with continuous signs for ≥6 months). Must include at least one of: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech. Significant functional impairment. Prevalence ~1%."},
{id:"nce-165",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'positive symptoms' of schizophrenia?",options:["Good things","Excess or distortion of normal functions: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech/behavior","A type of medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Positive symptoms = additions to normal experience. Includes: delusions (fixed false beliefs), hallucinations (perceptions without stimulus — often auditory), disorganized speech/behavior, abnormal motor behavior (catatonia). Typically respond to antipsychotic medication. The 'psychotic' features. Distinct from negative symptoms."},
{id:"nce-166",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'negative symptoms' of schizophrenia?",options:["Bizarre behaviors","Loss or decrease in normal function: affective flattening, alogia, avolition, anhedonia, asociality","A type of medication","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Negative symptoms = losses/deficits. 5A's: Affective flattening, Alogia (poverty of speech), Avolition (lack of motivation), Anhedonia (inability to experience pleasure), Asociality (lack of interest in relationships). Often more disabling than positive symptoms. Less responsive to medication. Major focus of recovery-oriented care."},
{id:"nce-167",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'delusion'?",options:["An idea","A fixed, false belief that is not amenable to change despite conflicting evidence","A hallucination","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"A delusion: a fixed, false belief held despite evidence to the contrary, and not consistent with the person's cultural/religious background. Types: persecutory (most common), grandiose, erotomanic, somatic, referential, nihilistic, bizarre. Bizarre = implausible. Distinguish from overvalued idea (held less firmly, often with some doubt)."},
{id:"nce-168",q:"Which of the following BEST describes a 'hallucination'?",options:["A belief","A perception-like experience without external stimulus; can occur in any sensory modality (most often auditory)","A delusion","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"A hallucination: a perception-like experience without external stimulus. Can be in any modality: auditory (most common, often voices in schizophrenia), visual (more common in medical conditions, delirium), olfactory, gustatory, tactile. Auditory hallucinations: command (must be assessed for risk), commenting, conversing, somatic."},
{id:"nce-169",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Schizoaffective Disorder'?",options:["Schizophrenia only","A psychotic disorder with a major mood episode (depression or mania) concurrent with Criterion A of schizophrenia, plus 2+ weeks of psychosis without mood symptoms","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Schizoaffective: psychotic disorder + a major mood episode (MDE or manic), with the psychotic symptoms occurring for ≥2 weeks in the absence of the mood symptoms (distinguishing it from MDD/mania with psychotic features). Subtypes: bipolar type and depressive type. Requires careful history to distinguish from schizophrenia and MDD with psychotic features."},
{id:"nce-170",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Brief Psychotic Disorder'?",options:["Schizophrenia","A psychotic disorder with sudden onset of psychotic symptoms lasting at least 1 day but less than 1 month, with eventual full return to premorbid functioning","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Brief psychotic disorder: sudden onset (within 2 weeks) of psychotic symptoms (delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech, grossly disorganized/catatonic behavior) lasting 1 day to 1 month. Eventually full return to premorbid functioning. Often associated with stress. Schizophreniform is 1-6 months; schizophrenia is 6+ months."},
{id:"nce-171",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Delusional Disorder'?",options:["Bizarre behavior","One or more delusions for at least 1 month, without other psychotic symptoms, with relatively preserved functioning outside the delusion","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Delusional disorder: 1+ delusions for ≥1 month. Criterion A symptoms of schizophrenia not present (no hallucinations, disorganized speech, etc.). Behavior is not obviously odd or bizarre outside the delusion. Functioning is relatively preserved. Types: erotomanic, grandiose, jealous, persecutory, somatic, mixed."},
{id:"nce-172",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'Antisocial Personality Disorder' (DSM-5-TR)?",options:["Shy","A pattern of disregard for and violation of the rights of others, occurring since age 15, with evidence before 18 of Conduct Disorder","A test","A diagnosis of childhood"],answer:1,explanation:"ASPD: a pervasive pattern of disregard for and violation of the rights of others since age 15. Includes: failure to conform to social norms, deceitfulness, impulsivity, irritability/aggressiveness, reckless disregard for safety, consistent irresponsibility, lack of remorse. Must have evidence of Conduct Disorder before 18."},
{id:"nce-173",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Borderline Personality Disorder' (BPD)?",options:["Mood disorder","A pervasive pattern of instability in interpersonal relationships, self-image, affects, and marked impulsivity, beginning in early adulthood","A test","A psychotic disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"BPD: pervasive pattern of instability in relationships, self-image, affect, and marked impulsivity. 5+ of 9: frantic efforts to avoid real/imagined abandonment, unstable relationships, identity disturbance, impulsivity in 2+ areas (spending, sex, substance, etc.), suicidal behavior/gestures, affective instability, chronic emptiness, inappropriate anger, transient stress-related paranoid ideation or dissociative symptoms."},
{id:"nce-174",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Narcissistic Personality Disorder' (NPD)?",options:["Low self-esteem","A pervasive pattern of grandiosity, need for admiration, and lack of empathy","A test","A psychotic disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"NPD: pervasive pattern of grandiosity (in fantasy or behavior), need for admiration, and lack of empathy. 5+ of 9: grandiose sense of self-importance, fantasies of unlimited success/power, believes 'special' and superior, requires excessive admiration, sense of entitlement, exploitative, lacks empathy, envious, arrogant. Vulnerable narcissism is a recognized variant."},
{id:"nce-175",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'treatment' for personality disorders?",options:["Medication only","Long-term psychotherapy is the primary treatment; specific approaches include DBT (BPD), TFP and MBT (BPD, ASPD), schema therapy, mentalization-based therapy","A test","Brief therapy"],answer:1,explanation:"Personality disorders are deeply ingrained, so long-term therapy is primary. Evidence-based approaches: DBT (BPD), Transference-Focused Psychotherapy (TFP), Mentalization-Based Therapy (MBT), Schema Therapy, Good Psychiatric Management (GPM). Medications are adjunctive for specific symptoms (e.g., SSRIs for affective dysregulation in BPD)."},
{id:"nce-176",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Dialectical Behavior Therapy' (DBT) for BPD?",options:["Insight only","A CBT-based, comprehensive treatment combining individual therapy, skills group, phone coaching, and therapist consultation team","A test","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"DBT (Linehan) for BPD: four modes — individual therapy (weekly), skills group (weekly), between-session phone coaching, therapist consultation team. Four skills modules: Mindfulness, Distress Tolerance, Emotion Regulation, Interpersonal Effectiveness. Dialectics: balance acceptance and change. Strong evidence base for BPD, also used for other populations."},
{id:"nce-177",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'OCD' (Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder)?",options:["A personality quirk","A disorder with obsessions (recurrent intrusive thoughts) and/or compulsions (repetitive behaviors) that are time-consuming or cause significant distress","A type of anxiety","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"OCD: obsessions and/or compulsions. Obsessions: recurrent, persistent, intrusive, unwanted thoughts/urges/images that cause anxiety/distress. Compulsions: repetitive behaviors (hand washing, checking, counting) or mental acts (praying, counting) aimed at reducing anxiety. The person recognizes (usually) that these are excessive. Time-consuming (>1 hour/day) or significant impairment."},
{id:"nce-178",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'ERP' (Exposure and Response Prevention) for OCD?",options:["A medical treatment","The gold standard behavioral treatment for OCD: gradual, repeated exposure to feared stimuli while preventing the compulsive response","A test","A type of medication"],answer:1,explanation:"ERP is the most evidence-based treatment for OCD. The client is exposed (in vivo or imaginal) to anxiety-provoking stimuli (triggers) while refraining from the compulsive response. Over time, anxiety decreases (habituation) and the client learns that the feared consequence doesn't occur. Often combined with cognitive therapy. SSRIs are also first-line."},
{id:"nce-179",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Body Dysmorphic Disorder' (BDD)?",options:["Anorexia","Preoccupation with one or more perceived defects in physical appearance that are not observable or appear slight, with repetitive behaviors or mental acts","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"BDD: preoccupation with ≥1 perceived defects in physical appearance that are not observable or appear slight to others. Causes significant distress or impairment. Repetitive behaviors (e.g., mirror checking, excessive grooming, skin picking) or mental acts (comparing appearance). Insight may be good, fair, or absent. Often comorbid with OCD. CBT and SSRIs are evidence-based."},
{id:"nce-180",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Hoarding Disorder'?",options:["A type of OCD","Persistent difficulty discarding or parting with possessions, regardless of their value, due to a perceived need to save them and distress associated with discarding","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Hoarding disorder: persistent difficulty discarding possessions (regardless of value), perceived need to save them, and distress when discarding. Results in cluttered living spaces that compromise use. Often associated with perfectionism, indecisiveness, avoidance, and difficulty organizing. Treatment: CBT tailored for hoarding (motivational interviewing, sorting, decision-making skills, exposure)."},
{id:"nce-181",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Trichotillomania' (Hair-Pulling Disorder)?",options:["A type of OCD","A body-focused repetitive behavior disorder: recurrent pulling out of one's hair, leading to hair loss, with repeated attempts to stop","A test","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Trichotillomania: recurrent pulling out of hair, leading to hair loss. Repeated attempts to decrease or stop. Causes significant distress or impairment. Tension before pulling; pleasure, gratification, or relief when pulling. Often occurs during sedentary activities (reading, watching TV). Treatment: habit reversal training (HRT), CBT, ACT, N-acetylcysteine (some evidence)."},
{id:"nce-182",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Excoriation Disorder' (Skin-Picking)?",options:["A skin disease","A body-focused repetitive behavior disorder: recurrent skin picking leading to skin lesions, with repeated attempts to stop","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Excoriation disorder: recurrent skin picking resulting in skin lesions. Repeated attempts to decrease or stop. Causes significant distress. Often in response to skin irregularities (bumps, scabs). Treatment: habit reversal training (HRT), CBT, ACT, sometimes SSRIs. Often comorbid with OCD, BDD, and other repetitive behaviors."},
{id:"nce-183",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'ADHD' (Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder)?",options:["A learning disability","A neurodevelopmental disorder with persistent inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning","A mood disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"ADHD: persistent pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning. Symptoms present before age 12 (at least 6 months, ≥6 symptoms in either or both categories). Subtypes: Predominantly Inattentive, Predominantly Hyperactive-Impulsive, Combined. Often comorbid with anxiety, depression, LD."},
{id:"nce-184",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Autism Spectrum Disorder' (ASD)?",options:["A personality disorder","A neurodevelopmental disorder with persistent deficits in social communication/interaction and restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior, interests, or activities","A mood disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"ASD: persistent deficits in social communication and social interaction (social-emotional reciprocity, nonverbal communication, developing/maintaining relationships) + restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior, interests, or activities. Symptoms in early childhood. Severity: Level 1 (requiring support), Level 2 (substantial), Level 3 (very substantial). Spectrum reflects range of abilities and needs."},
{id:"nce-185",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'neurodiversity' perspective?",options:["A medical view","The view that neurological differences (ADHD, autism, etc.) are natural variations of the human genome, not deficits to be cured","A diagnosis","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Neurodiversity: the perspective that neurological differences (ADHD, autism, dyslexia, etc.) are natural human variations, not diseases to be cured. Strengths-based view. Many self-advocates prefer accommodations, acceptance, and support over 'fixing.' Influences modern approaches to neurodevelopmental conditions."},
{id:"nce-186",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Specific Learning Disorder'?",options:["A type of mental retardation","A neurodevelopmental disorder with persistent difficulties in learning academic skills (reading, math, written expression) for at least 6 months","A test","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Specific Learning Disorder: persistent difficulties in reading (dyslexia), mathematics (dyscalculia), or written expression (dysgraphia) for ≥6 months, despite intervention. Affect ~5-15% of people. Not better explained by intellectual disability, sensory issues, or inadequate instruction. Often co-occurs with ADHD and other conditions."},
{id:"nce-187",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Intellectual Disability' (Intellectual Developmental Disorder)?",options:["A learning disability","Deficits in intellectual functioning and adaptive functioning (conceptual, social, practical), with onset in the developmental period","A test","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Intellectual Disability (DSM-5-TR: Intellectual Developmental Disorder): deficits in intellectual functioning (reasoning, problem-solving, abstract thinking, academic learning) + deficits in adaptive functioning (conceptual, social, practical) with onset in the developmental period. Severity based on adaptive functioning: mild, moderate, severe, profound."},
{id:"nce-188",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Dissociative Identity Disorder' (DID)?",options:["Mood disorder","Disruption of identity with two or more distinct personality states that recurrently take control, with gaps in memory","A psychotic disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"DID: disruption of identity characterized by two or more distinct personality states (alters) that recurrently take control of behavior, with gaps in memory for everyday events. Common comorbidities: PTSD, depression, substance use, self-harm, suicide attempts. Often related to severe, prolonged childhood trauma. Controversial, but well-established in DSM-5-TR."},
{id:"nce-189",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Depersonalization/Derealization Disorder'?",options:["A psychotic disorder","Persistent or recurrent episodes of depersonalization (feeling detached from self) and/or derealization (world feels unreal)","A mood disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"DPDR: persistent or recurrent episodes of depersonalization (feeling detached from one's self, body, or thoughts — as if observing from outside) and/or derealization (the world feeling unreal, dreamlike, distorted). Reality testing remains intact (distinguishing it from psychosis). Causes significant distress. Common after trauma or stress."},
{id:"nce-190",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Dissociative Amnesia'?",options:["Memory loss due to medical condition","Inability to recall important autobiographical information, usually of a traumatic or stressful nature, that is inconsistent with ordinary forgetting","A dementia","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Dissociative amnesia: inability to recall important autobiographical information, usually of a traumatic or stressful nature. Can't be explained by ordinary forgetting. May be localized (specific period), selective (some events in a period), generalized (entire life), or continuous (from event to present). Not due to substance or neurological condition."},
{id:"nce-191",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Somatic Symptom Disorder'?",options:["A real disease","One or more somatic symptoms that are distressing, with excessive thoughts/feelings/behaviors related to the symptoms","A factitious disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Somatic symptom disorder: ≥1 somatic symptoms that are distressing, with excessive thoughts, feelings, or behaviors related to the symptoms. The symptoms may or may not have a medical explanation; the focus is on the distress and excessive response. Distinct from illness anxiety disorder (preoccupation but few/no symptoms) and factitious disorder (intentional feigning)."},
{id:"nce-192",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Conversion Disorder' (Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder)?",options:["Feigning","One or more symptoms of altered voluntary motor or sensory function that are incompatible with recognized neurological/medical conditions","A test","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Conversion disorder (FND): ≥1 symptoms of altered voluntary motor or sensory function (weakness, paralysis, abnormal movement, gait, speech, hearing, vision, sensation, seizures) that are incompatible with recognized neurological/medical conditions. Not intentionally produced or feigned. Often preceded by stress. May include la belle indifference."},
{id:"nce-193",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Illness Anxiety Disorder'?",options:["Somatic symptom disorder","Preoccupation with having or acquiring a serious illness, with minimal or no somatic symptoms","A test","A factitious disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Illness anxiety disorder: preoccupation with having or acquiring a serious illness, with high anxiety about health, excessive health-related behaviors (e.g., checking body repeatedly) or maladaptive avoidance. Somatic symptoms are not present or only mild. Lasts ≥6 months. Replaces hypochondriasis (now obsolete)."},
{id:"nce-194",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Factitious Disorder'?",options:["Malingering","Falsification of physical or psychological signs/symptoms, in oneself or another, to assume the sick role","A test","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Factitious disorder: intentional falsification of physical/psychological signs/symptoms in oneself (or imposed on another — factitious disorder imposed on another, formerly Munchausen by proxy). The motivation is to assume the sick role; external incentives are absent. Self-harm is common. Distinct from malingering (which has clear external incentives)."},
{id:"nce-195",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Malingering'?",options:["Factitious disorder","The intentional production of false or exaggerated symptoms for external gain (avoiding work, getting money, drugs)","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Malingering: intentional production of false or grossly exaggerated symptoms for external incentives (financial gain, avoiding work or legal consequences, obtaining drugs). Not a mental disorder. Differentiate from factitious disorder (sick role motivation) and somatic symptom disorder (unconscious excess). Often a forensic or insurance context."},
{id:"nce-196",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Paraphilias' and 'Paraphilic Disorders'?",options:["All paraphilias are disorders","Paraphilias = atypical sexual interests; Paraphilic Disorders = paraphilias that cause distress, impairment, or harm to others","A medical issue","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"A paraphilia is an atypical sexual interest (e.g., voyeuristic, exhibitionistic, fetishistic, sadistic, masochistic, pedophilic). A paraphilic disorder is a paraphilia that causes significant distress or impairment to the individual, or involves harm/risk of harm to others. Examples of disorders: voyeuristic disorder, exhibitionistic disorder, pedophilic disorder, sexual sadism disorder."},
{id:"nce-197",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Gender Dysphoria' (DSM-5-TR)?",options:["A paraphilia","A marked incongruence between one's experienced/expressed gender and assigned gender, lasting at least 6 months, with clinically significant distress or impairment","A personality disorder","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Gender dysphoria: marked incongruence between experienced/expressed gender and assigned gender, of at least 6 months' duration, with clinically significant distress or impairment. Six criteria (in adults): strong desire to be of the other gender, to be treated as the other gender, to have the primary and/or secondary sex characteristics of the other gender, strong conviction of having the typical feelings/reactions of the other gender."},
{id:"nce-198",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Sleep-Wake Disorders'?",options:["A medical issue","Disorders of sleep: insomnia, hypersomnolence, narcolepsy, breathing-related (sleep apnea), circadian rhythm, parasomnias, restless legs, substance/medication-induced","A test","A personality disorder"],answer:1,explanation:"Sleep-wake disorders: 10 disorders. Insomnia (difficulty initiating/maintaining sleep), hypersomnolence (excessive daytime sleepiness despite adequate sleep), narcolepsy (irresistible sleep attacks + cataplexy), breathing-related (obstructive sleep apnea), circadian rhythm (shift work, jet lag), parasomnias (nightmares, sleepwalking, sleep terrors), restless legs, substance/medication-induced. CBT-I is first-line for insomnia."},
{id:"nce-199",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Insomnia Disorder'?",options:["A normal issue","Dissatisfaction with sleep quantity or quality, with difficulty initiating, maintaining, or returning to sleep, at least 3 nights/week for ≥3 months","A test","A medical diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Insomnia disorder: dissatisfaction with sleep quantity/quality. Difficulty initiating sleep (DIS), maintaining sleep (DMS), or early morning awakening (EMA). ≥3 nights/week for ≥3 months (chronic). Causes significant distress or impairment. Not better explained by another condition. CBT-I (CBT for insomnia) is the first-line treatment."},
{id:"nce-200",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'CBT-I' (Cognitive Behavioral Therapy for Insomnia)?",options:["A medication","A first-line, multicomponent treatment for insomnia including stimulus control, sleep restriction, cognitive therapy, relaxation, and sleep hygiene","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"CBT-I: the most effective, durable treatment for chronic insomnia. Components: stimulus control (bed for sleep only), sleep restriction (limit time in bed to match sleep), cognitive therapy (address sleep-related worries), relaxation, sleep hygiene. Often 6-8 weekly sessions. First-line per AASM and ACP guidelines, more effective long-term than meds."},
{id:"nce-201",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'sleep hygiene'?",options:["A type of therapy","Behavioral and environmental recommendations to promote healthy sleep (consistent schedule, dark/cool room, no screens before bed, etc.)","A test","A diagnosis"],answer:1,explanation:"Sleep hygiene: behavioral and environmental practices for healthy sleep. Examples: consistent sleep/wake schedule, dark/cool room, no screens 1 hr before bed, avoid caffeine/alcohol late, regular exercise (not too close to bedtime), comfortable bed, use bed only for sleep/sex. Often part of CBT-I, but alone is usually insufficient for chronic insomnia."},
{id:"nce-202",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Adlerian therapy' (Individual Psychology)?",options:["A behavioral approach","A growth-oriented, holistic therapy focused on social interest, lifestyle, birth order, and the striving for significance/belonging","A psychoanalytic approach","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Adlerian therapy (Alfred Adler): holistic, growth-oriented, social. Key concepts: social interest (Gemeinschaftsgefühl), lifestyle, birth order, the striving for significance/belonging, inferiority/superiority striving, creative self, fictional finalism, early recollections. The task of therapy: reorientation, encouragement, helping the client develop social interest."},
{id:"nce-203",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Reality Therapy' (Glasser)?",options:["A psychoanalytic approach","A choice theory-based therapy that focuses on present behavior, choices, and meeting basic needs","A test","A type of CBT"],answer:1,explanation:"Reality therapy (William Glasser): choice theory. People are responsible for their choices. Focus on the present, on behavior, on meeting basic needs (survival, love/belonging, power, freedom, fun). The WDEP system: Wants, Doing, Evaluation, Planning. Counseling is teaching, not punishment. Focus on what the client is doing, not feelings."},
{id:"nce-204",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'choice theory' (Glasser)?",options:["A personality theory","A theory that all behavior is chosen and driven by the need to satisfy 5 basic needs (survival, love/belonging, power, freedom, fun)","A test","A medical theory"],answer:1,explanation:"Choice theory (Glasser): we can only control our own behavior. All behavior is our best attempt to satisfy one or more of 5 basic needs: survival, love/belonging, power (achievement/recognition), freedom (autonomy), and fun (enjoyment). Quality world: what we want from the people and things in our lives. Compare to external control psychology."},
{id:"nce-205",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Person-Centered/Client-Centered therapy' (Rogers)?",options:["A behavioral approach","A humanistic approach emphasizing the client's innate drive toward growth, with the counselor offering empathy, UPR, and congruence","A test","A psychoanalytic approach"],answer:1,explanation:"Person-centered therapy (Rogers): the client is the expert on themselves. The counselor offers three core conditions: empathy, UPR, congruence. Non-directive. Trust the client's capacity for growth. The 19 propositions of personality. 7 stages of process. Foundation of humanistic/existential counseling. Influenced by and influenced the person of the counselor movement."},
{id:"nce-206",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'the 19 propositions' of Rogers' personality theory?",options:["A test","A theory of personality development and functioning, with propositions about the organism, the self, and the tendency toward actualization","A medical theory","A medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Rogers' 19 propositions describe personality and behavior. Key: the organism has one basic tendency (actualizing). The self is a differentiated part of the experiential field. Incongruence between self and experience leads to psychological maladjustment. Fully functioning person: open to experience, existential living, organismic trusting, experiential freedom, creativity."},
{id:"nce-207",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'the fully functioning person' (Rogers)?",options:["A perfection","A person who is open to experience, lives existentially, trusts their organism, feels free, and is creative","A diagnosis","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"The fully functioning person (Rogers): 5 qualities — (1) openness to experience (no defensiveness), (2) existential living (present moment), (3) organismic trusting (trusts own gut), (4) experiential freedom (acts with awareness), (5) creativity. A process, not a destination. The opposite of the rigid, defended person. Not 'perfect' but alive and growing."},
{id:"nce-208",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Psychosynthesis' (Assagioli)?",options:["A behavioral therapy","An integrative approach that uses a model of the psyche (lower, middle, higher unconscious, superconscious, self) to integrate parts into a higher self","A test","A medical approach"],answer:1,explanation:"Psychosynthesis (Roberto Assagioli): integrates parts of the psyche into a higher self (not Freud's model). Layers: lower unconscious, middle unconscious, higher unconscious (superconscious), conscious self (or 'I'), and transpersonal self. Techniques: will, imagination, intuition. Used in spiritual, transpersonal, and integrative work."},
{id:"nce-209",q:"Which of the following BEST describes 'Integrative Therapy'?",options:["One theory","A theoretical integration of techniques and concepts from multiple theories into a coherent, unified framework","A test","A type of medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Integrative/theoretical integration combines theories and techniques into a new, coherent framework. Compare to technical eclecticism (Lazarus, choose techniques by client need without theoretical integration), assimilative integration (one main theory with techniques from others), and common factors (relationship is the active ingredient). Integrative therapists have a unified map."},
{id:"nce-210",q:"Which of the following BEST describes the 'wellness' model (Myers, Sweeney, Witmer)?",options:["A disease model","A holistic model of wellness including the body, mind, emotion, spirit, work, finances, and environment","A type of CBT","A test"],answer:1,explanation:"Wellness (Myers, Sweeney, Witmer): a holistic, positive model — Indivisible Self. Dimensions: Body, Mind, Emotion, Spirit, Work, Finance, Environment, plus the integrating essence of the Self. Counselors use it for assessment and intervention. Wellness is more than absence of disease — it's a way of being. Strengths-based."}
);
